segments.text: a hard time getting jobs for the students.
Was the faculty then fairly well fixed?
The faculty didn't move around much.
I think this is what I don't think we see.
I think I'd have to look in the book to check our registration and student numbers against dates, but I don't think the
if they couldn't work out and couldn't get jobs, they'd go to school.
I don't think the depression, and this is just my opinion now without looking at numbers, that I don't think the depression affected the registration at school.
Do you know anything about that?
I know that they hired a number of students to work for small wages and have a number of remembrances of them.
Did you hire any in your department to work for?
worked for y'all.
I know agriculture hired him.
Well, we used to have student labor and that type of thing.
To help out students who needed the money to go to school.
Yeah, we had that.
But I don't remember details about the actual 25 cents.
I mean, how much they paid.
I don't remember that.
Let's jump up a little ahead to the war years here in Indiana.
Were you here during the entire war years?

I can remember I had a one o'clock class and I can remember and that particular class it was a seminar class where the boys would get up and give a technical talk two things make them get more used to looking
stuff up in the literature, magazines, journals, and also getting up and presenting a technical talk.
And I can remember, and this was a one o'clock class, when I walked in that class that day,
So usually there was a lot of talk going on and kidding back and forth, getting ready for before class.
And everything was so solemn and the like.
And because these boys knew that they were going to be taken out before they had finished and the like.
And it was a solemn class.
They were taken out quite a bit early.
Mm-hmm.
Things must have slowed down a great deal during the war.
Yeah, that's right.
I think that's right.
Then, of course, well, in certain areas it blossomed because they brought in a lot of Army and Navy for special training classes and the like.
Did you handle any of those?
No, I didn't.
One of the things that I was quite active in was...
because so many of the men in industry, technical men in industry, were drafted out, or the industrial companies were handicapped.
And they started what they called engineering, science, management, or training.
In other words, the first job was to recruit teachers.
And mine was in chemical engineering.

And then recruit the industries to put on classes so that they could have classes to upgrade some of their lower class men so that they could replace the men who had been drafted out at higher levels.
And we taught a lot of those kind of things and engineers.
Were these short courses or full term courses?
No, they were usually about two months instead of three or four.
So these were really special students?
Oh yes, oh these were all special.
A course on heat transfer, a course on what they were.
So you really lost most of your four year students at that time.
Right, this is right.
Stayed on for two years.
I see.
Did you lose any...
This is why I'd be interested in checking dates with registration in the school.
Did you lose any of your staff because of the lighter load of students?
As I remember it, we did not.
I don't think we did.
Some of them, I think, went and... Then most of your work during the 40s was
during the war years was fairly well geared to the war itself and to the various facets of government programs.
Any others that stick out in your mind?
Anything that might be of interest to you?
Possibly a little known?
Any work you might have done here?
Programs directed?
No, I don't recall too much.
See, this was quite a few years ago, some of these questions.
Yes, I understand.
There's another.
You spoke, when we spoke together, about somebody I might suggest is...
There's a man here by the name of M.K.
Thornton.
His nickname is Duke, Duke Thornton, T-H-O-R-N-T-O-N. And he was one of the older time teachers, kind of a descriptive type when they were teaching chemical engineering from the descriptive courses.
And Don Harris, W.D.
Harris came here.
He just retired now.
And he's an Iowa State PhD man.
And he came here about 1935.
I came in 38.
And he probably, he knows a lot about the early, if you're trying to get early history and the like.
And Thornton, Duke Thornton, would know the real, if you really, he knows some of these very early presidents.
And he was telling me,
There's a men's garden club, and it meets once a month.
And I'm not a gardener, but a lot of my good friends go to it, so I go to this men's garden club mainly for the association rather than for any way.
And I used to take Duke to this men's garden club.
He's quite a talker, and he'd get talking some of these old presidents' way and the like.
He can, I think, give you a lot of early history.
Let me digress just a little bit here.
Drop back to when you first came here in 1938.
Could you give me some first impressions, what you thought about the school?
Was it just a sleepy little cow college?
Basically, it was a country boys' school.
One of the things that stands out in my mind was that so many of the boys were first generation of college students.
In other words, that's what kind of a boy I was when I was going to school.
And yet up north, a lot of these boy parents had been to college.
And when I came down here, why, these boys, their parents were farm workers or workers and had not been to college, educated, higher education.
Many of them had probably never been to high school.
Right.
And so that was one thing that I enjoyed working.
with these students who were first generation of college students, so anxious to learn, anxious to learn, and do a good job in school.
So you were very favorably impressed with the students?
Oh, I certainly was.
I certainly was.
And I think it's, I've enjoyed, I have enjoyed my work here very much.
Could you recall some of the people that you were most closely associated with or that you recall most favorably, people that made an impression on you?
Well, we were in this combined chemistry and chemical engineering under Dr. Hedges.
It was an old-timer F.F.
Bishop.
He'd been here.
I think came about 1924 or something of that nature, whereas I didn't come until 38.
Dr. Harris didn't come until 35.
And Old Bish was just a fine chap.
He died maybe 10 years ago, 15 years ago.
I don't know.
I should have these dates in mind.
But he was just, he came from upper New York State,
had gone to a small town in upper New York State.
He was a northern boy, but he'd come down here in 24 and had been here for a good many years before I ever landed here.
And he had some stories that it would really be nice to...
They used to have a trolley line between Bryan and College Station, and an actual trolley ran back.
And you'd see most of the...
Originally, most of the people would live on the campus.
They had campus houses where the professors lived.
And there's one right in back of where I live.
They moved many of those around College Station.
Right.
There's one man that bought ours, bought that one.
He used to be head of the publicity around here years ago.
And he bought it, and then he moved away and sold it to a Baptist minister, I believe.
And so there are a good many of those old campus houses.
There were many of them where Spence Park is now, over beside the corn dorms there.
There was a whole row there.
Well, then, so old Bishop, I remember, he used to like that.
He was not married.
He was a bachelor for many, many years.
And then eventually he did break down and get married.
He used to like to eat well and drink beer.
Not just drink beer.
He very seldom would drink any whiskey, but Old Fish was fine.
He had a stroke here several years ago.
And what was his position?
He taught chemical engineering.
And so the three of us made up that new department of chemical engineering.
Professor Harris, me, and F.F.
Bishop.
Do you have any interesting recollection, any interesting remembrance of Gib Gilchrist?
Well, he was a strict disciplinarian, and I believe in that.
I think he was
a very strict disciplinarian.
Well, I think I liked Mr. Gilchrist.
Of course, he's the one that hired me, really.
Got me started in this, so he helped get the college station started as a community.
That's where it got its name, Station on the Railroad, where I lived off to.
In your long tenure here, have you any thoughts on the involvement of the Corps of Cadets since you came here?
Seen any changes in it?
Well, it used to be mandatory, and everybody that came here had to take it.
But I thought it was a fine...
The students we got that way were very fine students.
It taught them discipline, taught them to do a job whether they wanted to or not, if they were asked to do it, whether they did it.
And their attitude, yes, sir.
I thought that was very good.
Very fine training.
Did you see any changes over the years in the Corps that you thought were good or bad?
Well, the first step was to let the boys go to school without necessarily taking Corps activities.
And the students did not like that, as far as I was concerned.
It worked out.
It was done gradually enough so that I saw no real detriment.
That didn't really happen, though, until after World War II, right?
I guess so.
So many civilian students.
They taught quite all kinds of classes during the war.
Code classes and electrical classes.
kind of trade school type of thing.
What were some of the more outstanding problems or situations?
Mr. Gilchrist?
I don't think he can put this.
You want me to turn this in?
No, it's nothing.
But I mean, he was very embarrassed when it happened.
They were having some kind of a formal
formal dinner and they served fried chicken or something like that.
And I know the lady that was sitting next to him, she was one of our good friends.
And one of them almost killed Chris, big chicken leg flew off the plate and went right in the middle of her lap and was he embarrassed.
Do you think he had a sense of humor?
Oh, I think he had a good sense of humor.
I might think of some of those things.
Were there any outstanding problems or situations that confronted you during your association with the college?
You've mentioned, one, the formation of the chemical engineering department.
Do you think of any major problems that had to be overcome?
situations which you encountered in your history here.
Well, it was this drinking problem with the...
Yes, you mentioned that.
Drinking problem.
Taking empty bottles home in their suitcases.
Let's solve that.
You mentioned you had problems with space
Well, when we were transferred out of the chemistry department,
Well, chemical engineering was just, teaching of chemical engineering was just changing as I came here.
And the laboratory work was just changing.
And they had just bought a bunch of equipment to teach the new type of chemical engineering teaching.
And we had just gotten it all installed over here in the old chemistry building.
Then about just after we got it installed, while we got moved over to the, of course, we were happy about getting moved out.
But then we had to reinstall it all over again.
So it was, but we used student labor for that.
We used a lot of student labor, and that was good for them.
Then we got into, we could cut a hole in the floor if we wanted the column to go up three stories.
We could cut a hole in the floor and we got in no trouble at all.
Just cut a hole in the floor.
Whereas in this brand new building we got, I don't think they'd like us cutting.
No, I don't think they'd appreciate that at all.
Do you feel that you had any important accomplishments while you were here at A&M?
Do you think you'd like to look back on any pride or viewing accomplishments?
Well, I think the feeling was good working with the students, a very good association with the students.
This is what I appreciate and I like.
Accomplishments I think was, I was not a big researcher, but I hired some people who were.
And I think one of the men that
took my place when I retired.
He's done very, very well here.
And the way he came here, I was teaching at North Carolina State before I came here, and I had a senior in there who stayed on teaching at North Carolina State.
And we got along well.
And so he had a boy come through that had been in the Navy and came back to talk to his teacher, which was one of my students, about graduate work.
It would be good to take graduate work.
Why don't you get out to Texas A&M?
Lindsey used to teach here, and he'll give you a good deal.
So Charlie Holland, Charles Holland, came down here with that recommendation.
And he's done real well.
He's developed a mathematical research and the like and done fine.
When it came my time to retire, I went in to see Dean Benson and told him he'd have to start looking around because I had to retire.
And he said, well, who would you recommend?
And so I told him, and I thought, Dr. Holland, if he searched the country over,
you would not find any better man to take my place.
So he hired him, and I think he's done real well.
And Professor Harris has done quite well in research on cottonseed oil and the like.
He has gotten a new idea recently,
using hydrogen as a fuel for automobiles instead of gasoline.
That's received some publicity.
And I think there's just been a recent article come out of MIT on the same basis.
Sort of a fuel cell type thing?
I think, no, just a combustion of hydrogen.
Rather than production of electricity.
Yeah, yeah, no.
Then we had a man here.
We hired a man.
Mr. Gilchrist wanted to get started.
And he hired a man by the name of Kirkbride, C.G.
Kirkbride, as a research professor, distinguished research professor.
And Kirkbride was working for an American oil company down in Texas City.
And he came in here, but he was a promoter.
And he used this job as a stepping stone to go to work for Sun Oil Company.
And he really did well.
He got himself on their board of directors and all of that.
He was with Sun Oil, so he really did a lot.
We've kept in touch with him.
He promoted himself.
He stayed here only about two years, almost.
And yeah, he did, but we still keep in touch with him.
Then they hired another man to take his place by the name of Murdock, M-U-R-D-O-C-H, who was really a theoretical boy.
He could lay on the mathematics and the like real high.
He eventually went to work for Dow Chemical Company and got moved down here in Texas City.
Freeport, Freeport instead of Texas City.
And then he got moved up to the Midland, big research there, Midland, Michigan.
There was a large research group and has done well.
So a lot of our
people, some of those people have used us as stepping stones.
But Don Harris, Professor Harris, he's an Iowa State man, he stayed here, came here before I did.
Then we had a man that
came here and got interested in cottonseed vegetable oils by the name of Bill Harris, W.B.
Harris.
And he's on the staff now.
He came up through the cottonseed research, oilseed research group.
And he's started some very interesting things in the department.
on stack sampling and that pollution and the like.
And he's had a group of people in from industry and have had short courses of people.
I think I attended to a couple of them.
Just some of my old students came in and the like.
Yeah, one of my students for lots of time, well, just
about a week ago.
One former student and his wife and daughter is coming.
His daughter is going to register here.
And they just stopped over to see us.
And he was making arrangements for her to get in the dormitory and that type of thing.
And so they just stopped over to see me.
What makes me feel a little bit, a little before that, one of the former students was in.
started telling me about his granddaughter had just been born.
So when my students start telling me about their grandchildren, it makes me wonder.
This was what you would consider then as your greatest success and accomplishment are your statements.
Right, that's right, that's right.
Well, I should have brought something over, but one of our students had been on the board of directors of Mobile Well Company,
done fine.
This picture was in their annual report and the like.
Those are the things that make you feel good.
That will give you a real sense of accomplishment, I'm sure.
Well, we've got them all.
We've got a lot of vice presidents.
Selenese Corporation is a very good company.
One of our boys is vice president of that.
These kind of things is what, of course,
We've got all kinds of boys, and one of the things that makes me feel good is some of the boys that had a heck of a hard time to get through have done very well after they get out.
And I think it was because they were used to working.
They had to work hard to get through, and they kept that working hard themselves after they got out.
Whereas some of these boys that had it easy to get through, they could coast, and so they coasted after they got out.
And these boys that had to work hard would go ahead of them.
And then what made me feel good, before we started graduate work here,
why I would encourage our boys to go to graduate school.
And we had a...
I got one up in Princeton, and he really did well.
And I'd see, I'd meet these people from this ASAS, Society of Engineering Education.
I got to know people all over the country through that organization.
And I got to know this...
head of the department at Princeton real well.
And he said, if you have any more boys like him, all you have to do is just tell him, I can recommend them.
And he'd get them in.
And we did that for three or four boys.
And he told me they'd put some, we'd had so many A&M boys up there, they'd put Texas A&M Research Laboratory.
And we had a fine relationship with Wisconsin, Michigan, Princeton.
So having that kind of a role was satisfying that one of our boys went from up to Wisconsin.
Now he's head of the research for the Standard Oil in New Jersey.
Or maybe not the head, but one of the higher ups in their research organization.
Mathis, M-A-T-H-I-S.
Oh, you know, Vice President of Shell, I don't think of his name, but he was down in one of their islands where they have a very large research, large operating refinery and the like.
You might, if you have some time, jot down a list of your distinguished students and those that have changed some continents.
We have an interest in people who have done this.
Manager of...
There's a big caustic soda plant, chlorine caustic soda, by mining salt, passing electricity through it.
You generate chlorine and make sodium hydroxide caustic soda.
And one of our boys had manned a big plant and those kind of things and all that.
Let's shift gears just a moment here and ask you what you might regard as some of the
greater weaknesses or failures or possibly lost opportunities or misdirections of the university during your association?
Just a little bit critical if you can.
Think of anything that might have been better had it not occurred or some changes.
Well, I think some of these changes have been made.
Getting a little more cultural material in our courses.
I think certainly you need to know a lot of mathematics and science and the like, but I think they put in a little bit more education in English and that type of thing, which I think is good.
I think that's very important.
Yeah, I think so too.
I used to encourage students to...
take more of that.
In other words, one complained to me how the English department used to make them write.
He didn't like that.
And so the way I counteracted that was, the only way your boss up on top above your immediate superior, but two or three, four notches up, is reports which you write and get sent upstairs.
And if you don't know how to write a good report,
Why, the better you can make a report that's going upstairs, the better off you'll be considered by those that have something to say.
So I was encouraging people to not look down on English as a tool, really.
In other words, the more liberal arts that an engineer could take, the more well-rounded an engineer could become.
That's right.
That's exactly right.
I think there's a trend by many people today to try to take the liberal arts out.
I've heard some engineering people who would like to get more pure engineering in and reduce the number of liberal arts courses.
Well, I think that's very interesting.
What do you regard as some of the more outstanding changes that have occurred at A&M during your association?
Well, I think all of this.
Getting in, well, it's far enough past now, I think, is letting students in, civilian students.
I think this is a good idea.
And letting the girls in, I think, is a good idea.
It seems like our tremendous growth has occurred after we began to let girls in.
Well, again, I think there's a limit
on growth, too.
Yes.
I think there's a limit on growth, too, but the same.
Well, I think broadening the school from a strictly military school, I think, was a good idea.
I think then we are becoming a university.
Right.
That's right.
I have one personal question.
Well, not really personal.
On some research I was doing, did you ever know a man by the name of G.S.
Fraps?
Fraps?
Oh, you mean the old-timer?
Yeah.
Did you know?
He used to live right down the street from me.
He was a state chemist, and then he went on to TVA, I believe.
Not Asbury.
I'm talking about Fraps.
Asbury's later.
Fraps.
Fraps was an old-timer.
He was a character.
I knew him personally.
You did?
Oh, yeah.
But some of the stories that they used to tell about him
He wrote prolifically.
I have stacks and stacks of things.
He did a lot of work for the experiment station.
He did most of their fertilizer analysis.
Many of their feed analysis.
And I was simply wondering about him.

We were doing a bibliography on the experiment station, and I kept running across this man, Fraps, who'd been here for, seemed like he put first articles in the 1890s and by the late 1830s, I mean 1930, he's still writing.
And I just wondered what kind of man he was.
Well, he was a very penny pincher.
He was frugal.
Very frugal.
He used to give out.
He ran that office just like Hedges used to run his operation.
They had to come and ask him for a pencil.
And then they'll say to whittle their pencil down to that long white.
You wouldn't give them a knowing.
This is a story I've heard.
I didn't work there, but they say he was a very, there are some old stories about old Frapps, which would be very good to...
I think he was something of a campus character then.
Yeah, he was.
Then evidently one of his replacements...
Sam Asbury also became something of a campus character, too.
Well, I was just curious about that.
That was something I hadn't run across, and I hadn't run across any files on it.
You might want to talk to this fellow, Duke Thornton.
He's an old-timer around here.
Okay, I'll do that.
Then there's another man you may wish to talk to, although I don't know how... His name is Snuggs.
S-N-U-G-G-S, I guess.
I think he lives up on Harrington.

But he has, his memory failed him, and you may, I think it'd be good to talk to him and see what you can get out of him, but I've heard that his memory has failed some, but it doesn't every, I'm, I know that I have a harder time to
bring things up out of the past.
One man says, well, it goes in one ear and out the other.
Well, maybe really that happens because there's nothing in between to stop it.
Let me turn this off.
OK, you were.
OK, I'm going to tell you how I got into politics.
There used to be part of the state constitution that said,
that you could not draw state pay and still hold a position of honor and trust outside of your job.
And the city of College Station was incorporated.
Some was, I don't know, about 38 or 40, something in that region, about 40, say.
And we had no trouble of having our city council elected from the staff.
There was no trouble at all.
And then the city did not put a street, or they did put a street, where some individual did not want that street or wanted the street and didn't get it.
And he got mad at the city council, and he found this statement in the Constitution.
And he brought suit against the college for paying the state pay because these people held a position of honor and trust as a city council member.
Who brought suit?
Do you remember his name?
Well, I'll probably think of it and just...
I hope before I leave.
And so as soon as...
this suit was legally brought, the college stopped paying these people who were on the city council.
And one of my good friends was in that position, and he came to me and asked me if I would run in his place so he could get his money from the college.
And so I agreed to do that, and I happened to win.
Who was this that came to you?
I'll get all of this.
But the interesting thing about it, to continue that a little further, was that instead of paying these people, the college put it in the bank.
And once their successor was legally sworn in,
And these people got all of their back pay in one big lump sum.
Well, at least they didn't lose it.
Yeah.
Well, I'll get you these names.
So you went ahead and you were elected when?
1971, was it?
I guess so.
Are you still serving on the city?
No.
Go a little bit farther.
Is there anything interesting that happened while you were on the city council that might be interesting?
worthy of note if anybody ever wants to write anything about the history of College Station.
Can you think of any big decisions that were made or weighty proposals that came before the council?
No, I'll write off hand.
On the spur of the moment, it takes time to have those things come up.
Fred Bryson is still...
Yes, I've got to talk to him.
We have a short tape that was made by Henry Devloff.
about 30 minutes.
I've got to listen to that before I go talk to him again, make sure I don't duplicate any material.
He likes to talk.
I'm sure he'd be a good one to do.
Fred Bryson likes to talk?
Oh, yes, yes.
Well, he's a...
I have a very high opinion of Fred Bryson, too.
Yeah, he came out.
I'm a Little League coach.
He...
